-168-26-0070</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The importance of catalysis and sustainable production in modern society cannot be underestimated as major technologies.The aim of this project was to develop resources and practical activities on these topics that would be suitable for a lay audience.Targets are information leaflets, and practical workshops to be delivered to large numbers of members of the general public during Science week, and to school groups initially in Southampton.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project sits within a larger EU Network of Excellence collaboration - IDECAT - funded through the EU FP6 programme. A further target is to share the new resources with European partners in the network to maximise their use, and contribute to increased public appreication of the importance of the scientific research underpinning these technologies. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1834</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Materials Matter! - Nanocatalysts and Sustainable Production</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an open day or visit at my research institution</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>192E238F-725D-4D1B-8149-476F252E36F3</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Created and deliverd a hands-on activity for the public to engage with the research in Southampton associated with nanocatalysis and sustainable production. This includes leaflets, demonstrations, hands-on experiments for the public and related posters and exhibits. The materials were used primarily at the Southampton Science and Engineering Day in March (and in several years). Elements were also used for schools visits and demo talks given by the organiser, colleagues and students in Southampton.

